.SH NAME
.PP
\f[B]pmreorder\f[] \-\- performs persistent consisteny check using store
reordering mechanism
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$\ python\ pmreorder\ <options>
\f[]
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The pmreorder tool is a collection of python scripts designed to parse
and replay operations logged by pmemcheck \- a persistent memory
checking tool.
.PP
Pmreorder performs store reordering between prersistent memory barriers
\- a sequence of flush\-fence operations.
It uses the consistency checking routine provided in the command line
options to check whether the files are in a consistent state.
.PP
Seeing as the combination of valgrind and the multiple store reordering
will take a lot of time to process, it would be beneficial to do as
little stores as possible to verify whether the tested program is
powerfail safe.
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
\f[C]\-h,\ \-\-help\f[] Prints synopsis and list of options.
.PP
\f[C]\-l\ <store_log>,\ \-\-logfile\ <store_log>\f[] The pmemcheck log
file to process.
.PP
\f[C]\-c\ <prog|lib>,\ \-\-checker\ <prog|lib>\f[] Consistency checker
type.
.PP
\f[C]\-p\ <path>,\ \-\-path\ <path>\f[] Path to the consistency checker.
.PP
\f[C]\-n\ <name>,\ \-\-name\ <name>\f[] The name of the consistency
checking function within the library.
.PP
\f[C]\-t\ <print|file>,\ \-\-output_type\ <print|file>\f[] Set the
logger type.
Default value is \f[C]print\f[].
.PP
\f[C]\-o\ <pmreorder_output>,\ \-\-output\ <pmreorder_output>\f[] Set
the logger output file.
(If \f[C]\-t\f[] option is set to \f[C]file\f[]).
.PP
\f[C]\-e\ <debug|info|warning|error|critical>,\ \ \-\-output_level\ <debug|info|warning|error|critical>\f[]
Set the output log level.
.PP
\f[C]\-r\ \ <full|noreorder|accumulative|partial>,\ \ \-\-default_engine\ \ <full|noreorder|accumulative|partial>\f[]
Set the default reorder engine.
Default value is \f[C]full\f[].
.SH ENGINES
.PP
By default all possible permutations of stores are tested.
.PP
In such case to check consistency of stores between barriers pmreorder
uses \f[C]full\f[] reorder engine.
It means that for each set of stores it generates all possible
permutations to check.
This may takes a significant amount of time, so there is avaiable a few
more types of engines to limit number of tested sequences:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]noreorder\f[] \- pass set of stores unchanged, do check on the
original collection.
It can be useful for less significant parts of code.
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
Example:
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ input:\ (a,\ b,\ c)
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ output:\ (a,\ b,\ c)
\f[]
.fi
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]accumulative\f[] \- perform check on growing sequences
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
Example:
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ input:\ (a,\ b,\ c)
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ output:
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ ()
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (\[aq]a\[aq])
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (\[aq]a\[aq],\ \[aq]b\[aq])
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (\[aq]a\[aq],\ \[aq]b\[aq],\ \[aq]c\[aq])
\f[]
.fi
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]partial\f[] \- generates a sequence of all possible combinations
without replacement of stores (limited to 1000), and then select from
them random 3 sequences to run under consistency checker.
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
\ Example:
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ input:\ (a,\ b,\ c)
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ output:
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (\[aq]b\[aq],\ \[aq]c\[aq])
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (\[aq]b\[aq],)
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (\[aq]a\[aq],\ \[aq]b\[aq],\ \[aq]c\[aq])
\f[]
.fi
.SH INSTRUMENTALIZATION
.PP
Another way to switch types of reordering is to use Valgrind\-pmemcheck
instrumentalization at runtime within the tested program.
.PP
Exposed macros:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]VALGRIND_LOG_STORES\f[]
.PP
Start logging memory operations.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]VALGRIND_NO_LOG_STORES\f[]
.PP
Stop logging memory operations.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]VALGRIND_FULL_REORDED\f[]
.PP
Issue a \f[I]full\f[] reorder log.
For more details see ENGINES section above.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]VALGRIND_PARTIAL_REORDER\f[]
.PP
Issue a \f[I]partial\f[] reorder log.
For more details see ENGINES section above.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]VALGRIND_ONLY_FAULT\f[]
.PP
Issue a log to disable reordering.
For more details see \f[I]noreorder\f[] engine in ENGINES section above.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]VALGRIND_STOP_REORDER_FAULT\f[]
.PP
Issue a log to disable reordering as \f[B]VALGRIND_ONLY_FAULT\f[], but
additionally disables consistency checker.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]VALGRIND_DEFAULT_REORDED\f[]
.PP
Issue a log to set the default reorder engine.
(Previously set with \-\-default_engine or \-r option, see OPTIONS
section above).
.SH PMEMCHECK STORE LOG
.PP
To generate \f[I]store_log\f[] for \f[B]pmreorder\f[] run pmemcheck with
additional parameters:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
valgrind\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-\-tool=pmemcheck\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-q\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-\-log\-stores=yes\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-\-print\-summary=no\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-\-log\-file=store_log.log\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-\-log\-stores\-stacktraces=yes\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-\-log\-stores\-stacktraces\-depth=2\ \\
\ \ \ \ \-\-expect\-fence\-after\-clflush=yes\ \\
\ \ \ \ test_binary.exe\ writer_parameter
\f[]
.fi
.PP
For further details of pmemcheck parameters see pmemcheck
documentaion (https://github.com/pmem/valgrind/blob/pmem-3.13/pmemcheck/docs/pmc-manual.xml)
.SH EXAMPLE
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
python\ pmreorder.py\ \\
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \-l\ store_log.log\ \\
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \-r\ partial\ \\
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \-t\ file\ \\
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \-o\ pmreorder_out.log\ \\
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \-c\ prog\ \\
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \-p\ test_binary.exe\ checker_parameter
\f[]
.fi
.PP
If any issue occures during \f[B]pmreorder\f[] analisys, inconsistent
stores are logged to pmreorder_out.log.
